{{Infobox writer | name = Gedaliah Alon | native_name = גדליה אלון | native_name_lang = he | image = Gedalia-Alon.jpg | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = Gedaliah Rogozitski | birth_date = 1901 | birth_place = [[Kobryn]], [[Russian Empire|Russian]]-ruled [[Congress Poland|Poland]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1950|3|17|1901}} | death_place = [[Israel]] | occupation = Historian | language = [[Hebrew]] | citizenship = [[Israel]]i | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = | spouse(s) = | partner(s) = | children = | relative(s) = | awards = [[Israel Prize]] (1953) | signature = | signature_alt = | website = | portaldisp = }}
'''Gedaliah Alon''' ({{lang-he|גדליה אלון}}; 1901–1950) was an [[Israeli people|Israeli]] [[historian]].
==Biography== Gedaliah Rogoznitski (later Alon) was born in 1901 in [[Kobryn]], [[Belarus]] (then in [[Russian Empire|Russian]]-ruled [[Congress Poland|Poland]]). In 1924, he studied for a year at [[Humboldt University of Berlin|Berlin University]] and, in 1926, he [[Aliyah|emigrated]] to the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate of Palestine]] and continued his studies at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]. He later joined the faculty of the Hebrew University.
==Awards and recognition== In 1953, three years after his death, Alon was posthumously awarded the [[Israel Prize]] for [[Jewish studies]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cms.education.gov.il/educationcms/units/prasisrael/tashyag/tashkab_tashyag_rikuz.htm?dictionarykey=tashyag |title=Israel Prize recipients in 1953 (in Hebrew) |publisher=Israel Prize Official Site |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110819115026/http://cms.education.gov.il/educationcms/units/prasisrael/tashyag/tashkab_tashyag_rikuz.htm?dictionarykey=tashyag |archivedate=19 August 2011 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> the inaugural year of the prize.
==Published works== * ''Jews, Judaism, and the Classical World: Studies in Jewish History in the Times of the Second Temple and Talmud''; translated from the Hebrew by Israel Abrahams, Jerusalem: Magnes Press, the Hebrew University, 1977. * ''The Jews in their Land in the Talmudic Age (70-640 C.E.)''; translated and edited by Gershon Levi, Jerusalem: Magnes Press, the Hebrew University, 1980-1984; Cambridge, Mass.: Harvard University Press, 1989.
