'''Valerie Sutton''' (born February 22, 1951) is an American developer of movement notation and a former [[dance]]r.

==Early life==
She was born in the borough of [[Manhattan]], in [[New York City]], the daughter of a [[physics|physicist]] father and a [[poetry|poet]]/[[Model (person)|model]] mother. She has an older sister Pam, a doctor of [[medicine]].<ref name=SuttonOrg>{{cite web|url=http://www.valeriesutton.org/|title=Valerie Sutton, Inventor Sutton Movement Writing & Shorthand|first=Valerie|last=Sutton|website=www.valeriesutton.org}}</ref>

At the age of six months, she moved with her family to [[Corning (city), New York|Corning, New York]], the home of the [[Corning Glass Works]], where her father became a physicist. She lived in Corning until the age of eight years, and then moved to [[Corona del Mar, California|Corona del Mar]], a part of [[Newport Beach, California]]. She spent the rest of her childhood in Corona del Mar, and as an adult moved to the [[San Diego, California]] area, where she has since lived. Her current home is in the San Diego suburb of [[La Jolla, California|La Jolla]].<ref name=SuttonOrg/>

==Developed==
In California, she credits the influence of [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]] [[animation]], as well as the theater and dance environment of [[Hollywood, California|Hollywood]] for directing her interest toward movement.<ref name=SuttonOrg/>

She developed the system known as [[MovementWriting|Sutton Movement Writing]] (lately also entitled the [[International Movement Writing Alphabet]] (the IMWA),<ref name=CSMW>{{cite web|url=http://movementwriting.org/|title=Sutton Movement Writing|first=Valerie|last=Sutton|website=movementwriting.org}}</ref> subdivided into five sections:

#[[DanceWriting]], which records [[dance]] [[choreography]]
#[[SignWriting]], which records [[sign language|signed languages]]
#[[MimeWriting]], which records classic [[mime artist|mime]] and [[gesture]]
#[[SportsWriting]], which records such activities as [[gymnastics]], [[ice skating]], [[skateboarding]] and [[karate]]
#[[ScienceWriting]], which records [[physical therapy]], [[body language]], [[animal]] movements, and other forms of movement<ref name=CSMW/>

The two forms of Sutton Movement Writing that have been most widely adopted<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stonehouses.co.uk/Signwriting.php|title=Wrights of Limm page on SignWriting|publisher=}}</ref> are DanceWriting and SignWriting<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nicaraguansignlanguageprojects.org/Links___SignWriting.php|title=Links & SignWriting|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.linguistics.berkeley.edu/sei/USR.html |title=University of California's list of scripts requiring Unicode representations |access-date=2010-05-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527032616/http://www.linguistics.berkeley.edu/sei/USR.html#n097 |archive-date=2010-05-27 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://doi.acm.org/10.1145/1292331.1292363|title=SignWriting on Mobile Phones for the Deaf|first1=Aisha Shamsuna|last1=Ahmed|first2=Daniel Su Kuen|last2=Seong|date=7 June 2017|publisher=ACM|via=ACM Digital Library|doi=10.1145/1292331.1292363}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uri.edu/iaics/content/2008v17n4/08%20Mihoko%20Kato.pdf|title=Mihoko Kato (Toyohashi University of Technology, Japan), A Study of Notation and Sign Writing Systems for the Deaf, in Intercultural Communication Studies XVII (2008)|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://homepage.uconn.edu/~hdv02001/Articles-pdfs/131%20-%20Notation%20Systems.pdf|title=Harry van der Hulst and Rachel Channon, Notation Systems|publisher=}}</ref><ref>Almasoud, Ameera M., and Hend S. Al-Khalifa. "SemSignWriting: A Proposed Semantic System for Arabic Text-to-SignWriting Translation." Journal of Software Engineering and Applications 5.8 (2012).</ref>

==Becoming a dancer==
DanceWriting was first developed in 1966, when Sutton was only 15, training as a professional [[ballet]] dancer. She invented a stick figure notation for her own personal use. Four years later she went to [[Copenhagen, Denmark]] to train with the [[Royal Danish Ballet]]. Over the next two years she applied her system to recording the historic ballet steps of the Royal Danish Ballet, which were in danger of being forgotten from lack of recording. The first DanceWriting textbook, ''Sutton Movement Shorthand, The Classical Ballet Key, Key One,'' was produced in December 1973. Within a year, it became outdated as Sutton improved her system. In the fall of 1974, by special invitation, she taught her system to the members of the RDB.

In 1974, articles about Sutton's DanceWriting system came to the attention of [[Lars van der Leith]], a sign language researcher, and others who worked with him at the [[Audiologopædisk Forskningsgruppe]] of the [[University of Copenhagen]], and they asked for a demonstration. As a result, van der Leith and his colleagues requested Sutton to develop a version of her movement notation adapted to the recording of sign languages. As a result, SignWriting was developed; it has been used for writing not only [[Danish Sign Language]], but the private sign language of a [[deaf]] South Pacific islander (in 1975), and [[American Sign Language]].

==Center for Sutton Movement Writing, Inc==
Sutton has continually worked to improve her notation systems and now leads the ''Center For Sutton Movement Writing, Inc.'' to spread her system.

==Wikimedia involvement==
[[File:Stephen_E_Slevinski_Jr,_with_Valerie_Sutton_%26_Interpreter_Pasch_McCombs.jpg|thumb|Valerie Sutton on the right, with Stephen E Slevinski Jr in the middle, at the NA Wiki Conference 2016.]]
Valerie Sutton was part of the ASL Wikipedia presentation at the [https://wikiconference.org/wiki/2016 North American Wiki Conference in 2016]. The presentation [https://wikiconference.org/wiki/Submissions:2016/Writing_the_American_Sign_Language_Wikipedia_on_Incubator "Writing the American Sign Language Wikipedia on Incubator"] involved 3 Deaf editors, Valerie Sutton, and Stephen E Slevinski Jr, along with 2 interpreters.

[[File:Explaining_ase_Wikipedia_at_SDPL_jeh.jpg|thumb|Valerie Sutton explaining the American Sign Language Wikipedia during NA Wiki Conference 2016]]
During the 2016 conference, Valerie Sutton explained the importance of the [https://incubator.wikimedia.org/wiki/Wp/ase American Sign Language Wikipedia]. She handed out several copies of the [http://www.signwriting.org/archive/docs12/sw1196_ASL_WIKIPEDIA_October_2016.pdf "ASL Wikipedia Excerpt booklet"].

